        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1979-11-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1979-11-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="280"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d280">
                <head>280. Summary of Conclusions of an Ad Hoc Group on China Meeting<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d280fn1">Source: Washington National Records Center,
                            <gloss target="#t_OSD_1">OSD</gloss> Files: <gloss target="#t_FRC_1"
                            >FRC</gloss> 330–82–0205, China (Nats), 19 November 79. Secret. The
                        meeting lasted from 11:44 a.m. until 12:02 p.m. The participants were
                            <persName corresp="#p_SRW_1">Sullivan</persName> from the Department of
                        State, <persName corresp="#p_MDE_1">McGiffert</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_AMA_1">Armacost</persName> from the Office of the Secretary
                        of Defense, <persName corresp="#p_OM_2">Oksenberg</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_HB_1">Huberman</persName> from the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Staff, and <persName corresp="#p_ADL_1"
                        >Aaron</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1979-11-15">November 15, 1979</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_ADL_1">David Aaron</persName> chaired a meeting of the Ad
                    Hoc Group on China to review planning for the <persName corresp="#p_BH_2"
                        >Brown</persName> trip.</p>
                <p>State, <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> agreed on the basic objectives of the trip which can now be
                    communicated to the Chinese. Our proposed agenda will cover assessments of the
                    global military balance, regional security issues, bilateral issues such as
                    subsequent contacts and export controls, and arms control.</p>
                <p>State, <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> concurred that the Chinese should be informed that General
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGM_1">Seignious</persName> will be a member of the
                    delegation and will seek to have talks with his Chinese counterpart.</p>
                <p>State, <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> concurred that <persName corresp="#p_BH_2">Brown</persName>
                    should seek to visit the industrial and military city of Wuhan in central China,
                    and should indicate a willingness to visit military installations in that
                    area.</p>
                <p>State and <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss> are to coordinate a paper on the
                    modality and timing for implementing a pro-China differential in <gloss
                        target="#t_COCOM_1">COCOM</gloss>, as Vice President <persName
                        corresp="#p_MW_1">Mondale</persName> had indicated to the Chinese we would
                    do. State, <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> agreed, however, that this issue should not be taken to <gloss
                        target="#t_COCOM_1">COCOM</gloss> until conclusion of Congressional action
                    on <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> and the Trade Agreement. If State and
                        <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss> cannot agree on the issue of modality,
                    a paper will go to the President on this issue.</p>
                <p>State, <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> agreed that <persName corresp="#p_ADL_1">David Aaron</persName>
                    should chair a working group to staff out papers on various arms control
                    measures which <persName corresp="#p_BH_2">Brown</persName> will convey to the
                    Chinese even prior to his trip. An important paper in this area concerns
                    encouraging the Chinese to test nuclear weapons underground. In no case would we
                    provide assistance that would help them perfect their nuclear capability.</p>
                <pb facs="1050" n="1011" xml:id="pg_1011"/>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> will task the Intelligence Community to
                    ascertain whether there is any evidence the Chinese may be involved in Pakistani
                    nuclear development.<note n="2" xml:id="d280fn2">On December 7, Bruce C. Clarke,
                        Deputy Director of the National Foreign Assessment Center of the <gloss
                            target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss>, sent a memorandum to the <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> in response to this request to evaluate
                        evidence on whether China was involved in Pakistan’s nuclear weapons
                        program. (Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Staff Material, Far
                        East, Box 26, <persName corresp="#p_OM_2">Oksenberg</persName>, Subject
                        File, <persName corresp="#p_BH_2">Brown [Harold]</persName> 1/80 Trip
                        Briefing Book, 12/79) <persName corresp="#p_OM_2">Oksenberg</persName>
                        summarized it in a December 12 memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1"
                            >Brzezinski</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_ADL_1"
                        >Aaron</persName>. (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
